## Error Handling Strategy

### Layered Error Handling

```
Switch TL1 error
  └─> switch1_menu.py raises exception
        └─> Flask route catches, returns 503 {"status": "error", "message": "..."}
              └─> Browser fetch() checks response.ok
                    └─> Notifications.show(data.message, "error")
```

### Error Response Catalogue

| Layer | Condition | Action |
|-------|-----------|--------|
| `app.py` startup | `patch_timers.json` malformed JSON | Log error + `sys.exit(1)` |
| `app.py` startup | Missing config keys | Log warning with key names + use defaults |
| `app.py` startup | Port in use | Log port conflict + `sys.exit(1)` |
| Flask route | TL1 connection failure | Return 503 |
| Flask route | TL1 query timeout (>10 s for power) | Return 504 |
| Flask route | Invalid port numbers | Return 400 |
| Flask route | Patch conflict | Return 409 |
| Flask route | Patch not found | Return 404 |
| Browser | Non-200 response | Display `message` in notification area |
| Browser | Network error (fetch throws) | Display "Network error — check lab connection" |
| Browser | Auto-refresh failure | Show stale-data banner; retain last known data |
| Browser | Power fetch failure | Show error; retain last power data |

### Stale Data Indicator

When `/api/ports` auto-refresh fails, the dashboard shows a yellow banner:

```
⚠ Data may be stale — last updated HH:MM:SS
```

This banner is cleared on the next successful refresh.

